  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Prayer to the Rain Master
  author: Lee Cham
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Consider the Rain Master, divine spirit,
    who weaves together yin and yang to form the vital breath,
    who commands the clouds and dragons to bestow grace.
    When wind and thunder merge, all crops and trees bow low;
    when rain and dew descend, all creatures revive and flourish.

    Our realm is blessed with virtuous sovereigns in succession,
    where timely rain and sunshine follow nature's course,
    where seasons harmonize and harvests overflow,
    and people receive heaven's abundant mercy.

    Yet the Japanese pirates lurk in their island strongholds,
    waiting in shadows, striking when they dare,
    brutalizing our innocent folk.
    Now our lord, righteous in his wrath, commands us forth
    to bring these brigands to account for their grave crimes.

    We march with thousands, sworn together,
    to strike their camps directly and utterly—
    as fire flushes the cunning hare from its burrow,
    as we topple the high nests of perched birds.

    O divine Rain Master, spirit most sacred,
    why not roll back the shadowed clouds,
    sweep away the pale mists with your hand,
    and let heaven's paths gleam clear and bright?
    Let the earth below grow dry and firm,
    that your celestial radiance shine eternal,
    so our soldiers need not spread their garments to dry,
    nor air their armor beneath the sun's face.

    Accept our reverent offering.
  footnotes:
    - This poem was written as a prayer to the rain deity before a military campaign against Japanese pirates (倭奴), who were frequent raiders on the Korean coast during the Joseon period.
    - The metaphors of flushing out rabbits and toppling bird nests represent the complete destruction of enemy forces.
    - The request for dry weather reflects practical military concerns of the time—armor and weapons needed to remain dry and functional for combat effectiveness.
